Chapter 15 — The Role of Symmetry in Physics

Symmetry is not a property of nature—it is the organizing principle.

Without symmetry, there would be no conservation laws. Energy could appear and disappear. Momentum could change arbitrarily. The universe would be chaos.

With symmetry, we have:

· Conservation laws that constrain motion
· Forces that emerge from gauge principles
· Classification of particles by their transformation properties
· Selection rules determining which processes can occur

The entire edifice of modern physics rests on symmetry.

